The headings in the right column are the **only** sections a slide may reference. If a needed scaffold doesn't exist in the repo, find another way — extra structure goes on the slide or in an interactive tool, not into the frozen repo.

## What teaching scaffolds on slides ARE allowed

Slides can still teach with structure that doesn't live in the repo (e.g. four failure-mode example cards, a worked example table row, a category gradient). What's forbidden is **promising students a repo capture surface that doesn't exist**.

If a slide shows fields like `_____` next to a "Capture in repo" header, those exact field names must exist in the repo. Otherwise, render them as on-slide thinking prompts (no `Capture in →` framing) or move them into the relevant interactive tool.

## When the user asks "is this slide mirroring the repo?"

Always read the repo file first, then audit each `Capture in →` and `Go to your repo →` reference against the actual sections and fields. Surface drift as a clear table (slide says X / repo has Y) before fixing.
